1. Launch EC2 Instance
Start a t2.micro EC2 instance using an Ubuntu AMI.
Configure the security group to allow:
HTTP (port 80) for web access.
SSH (port 22) for secure remote login.

2. Install Required Packages
SSH into the EC2 instance.
Update the instance and install Apache, MySQL, PHP, and WordPress dependencies:
sudo apt update
sudo apt install apache2 mysql-server php libapache2-mod-php php-mysql -y

3. Configure MySQL Database for WordPress
Secure the MySQL installation by setting a root password and removing unnecessary defaults:
sudo mysql_secure_installation
Create a WordPress database and user:
Log in to MySQL:
sudo mysql
Run the following SQL commands:
CREATE DATABASE wordpress;
CREATE USER 'wp_user'@'localhost' IDENTIFIED BY 'password';
GRANT ALL PRIVILEGES ON wordpress.* TO 'wp_user'@'localhost';
FLUSH PRIVILEGES;
EXIT;

4. Install and Configure WordPress
Download WordPress, extract it, and move it to the Apache web root directory:
wget https://wordpress.org/latest.tar.gz
tar -xvzf latest.tar.gz
sudo mv wordpress /var/www/html/
Configure WordPress to connect to the MySQL database:
Navigate to the WordPress directory:
cd /var/www/html/wordpress
sudo cp wp-config-sample.php wp-config.php
sudo nano wp-config.php
Update wp-config.php with database details:
define('DB_NAME', 'wordpress');
define('DB_USER', 'wp_user');
define('DB_PASSWORD', 'password');
define('DB_HOST', 'localhost');

5. Complete WordPress Setup and Create a Homepage
Open the public IP address of the EC2 instance in a browser.
Follow the WordPress setup steps to set up the site.
After setup, create a Welcome Page in WordPress and set it as the homepage:
In the WordPress dashboard, navigate to Pages > Add New.
Create a page titled "Welcome" with your desired content.
Go to Settings > Reading, select A static page, and set Welcome as the homepage.
